{% block head_styles %}
  <style>
    /* Longform editorial page on the site shell. Scoped .lang-* on site.css
       tokens, so it follows the light/dark toggle. Prose capped near 74ch. */

    .lang { max-width: 74ch; margin: 0 auto; padding: var(--gap-8) var(--gap-5) var(--gap-9); }

    .lang-eyebrow {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 12px;
      letter-spacing: 0.14em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--accent-deep);
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4);
    }
    .lang-title {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 400;
      font-size: clamp(30px, 5vw, 46px);
      line-height: 1.1;
      letter-spacing: -0.015em;
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4);
      color: var(--ink);
    }
    .lang-standfirst {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-size: 20px;
      line-height: 1.55;
      color: var(--ink-2);
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4);
    }
    .lang-updated {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 12.5px;
      letter-spacing: 0.04em;
      color: var(--accent-deep);
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-6);
      padding-bottom: var(--gap-5);
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    }

    .lang-sec { margin: var(--gap-7) 0 0; }
    .lang-sec__title {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-weight: 500;
      font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 28px);
      line-height: 1.2;
      letter-spacing: -0.01em;
      color: var(--ink);
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4);
    }

    .lang-body { font-family: var(--font-serif); font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--ink); }
    .lang-body p { margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4); }
    .lang-body p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .lang-body a { color: var(--accent-deep); }
    .lang-body strong { font-weight: 600; }

    /* Numbered streams. */
    .lang-streams { counter-reset: stream; list-style: none; margin: var(--gap-4) 0 0; padding: 0; }
    .lang-streams li {
      counter-increment: stream;
      position: relative;
      padding: 0 0 var(--gap-4) calc(var(--gap-6) + 6px);
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4);
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-size: 17px;
      line-height: 1.7;
      color: var(--ink);
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    }
    .lang-streams li:last-child { border-bottom: 0; padding-bottom: 0; margin-bottom: 0; }
    .lang-streams li::before {
      content: counter(stream);
      position: absolute;
      left: 0;
      top: 1px;
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 13px;
      font-weight: 500;
      color: var(--accent-deep);
      width: var(--gap-6);
      text-align: left;
    }

    /* Settled / being decided. */
    .lang-state { margin: var(--gap-4) 0 0; }
    .lang-state p { margin: 0 0 var(--gap-4); }
    .lang-state p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .lang-state strong { color: var(--accent-deep); }

    /* Progress log: a changelog. Each entry is a date plus a short paragraph,
       newest first. To add an entry, copy one .lang-log__entry block and put it
       at the top of the list. */
    .lang-log { margin: var(--gap-4) 0 0; border-left: 2px solid var(--rule); padding-left: var(--gap-5); }
    .lang-log__entry { margin: 0 0 var(--gap-5); }
    .lang-log__entry:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .lang-log__date {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 12.5px;
      letter-spacing: 0.04em;
      color: var(--accent-deep);
      margin: 0 0 var(--gap-2);
    }
    .lang-log__body {
      font-family: var(--font-serif);
      font-size: 16px;
      line-height: 1.65;
      color: var(--ink);
      margin: 0;
    }

    /* Sources. */
    .lang-sources { font-family: var(--font-sans); font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.55; list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: var(--gap-4) 0 0; }
    .lang-sources li { padding: var(--gap-3) 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); color: var(--ink-2); }
    .lang-sources li:last-child { border-bottom: 0; }
    .lang-sources a { color: var(--accent-deep); word-break: break-word; }

    .lang-byline {
      margin: var(--gap-7) 0 0;
      padding-top: var(--gap-5);
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
      font-family: var(--font-sans);
      font-size: 13px;
      line-height: 1.6;
      color: var(--ink-3);
    }

    @media (max-width: 640px) {
      .lang { padding: var(--gap-6) var(--gap-4) var(--gap-8); }
    }
  </style>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
<article class="lang">

  <header>
    <p class="lang-eyebrow">Practice · Language · 2026</p>
    <h1 class="lang-title">Keeping Anishinaabemowin alive: a working program</h1>
    <p class="lang-standfirst">A practice page. Updated as the work proceeds.</p>
    <p class="lang-updated">Last updated: June 12, 2026.</p>
  </header>

  <div class="lang-body">
    <p>This page documents a live program: a community-owned effort to record fluent speakers, build low-pressure places to hear and use Anishinaabemowin, and ship a modern course on technology the community controls. It is led by Russell Jones in Sagamok Anishnawbek and documented here as a working example of what Elder-first, consent-governed language technology looks like in practice.</p>
  </div>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">The numbers, plainly</h2>
    <div class="lang-body">
      <p>The 2021 Census counted 26,165 people in Canada who can hold a conversation in an Ojibway language, and 15,890 who have it as their mother tongue. The average age of that mother-tongue population is 48, the second oldest among the major Algonquian languages. Nearly half of today's speakers (47.5 percent) learned the language as a second language, the clearest sign that first-language transmission has thinned and learners are carrying more of the load.</p>
      <p>Use at home is the weakest link. Only about one in five Ojibway speakers uses the language most often at home, the lowest share among the large Algonquian languages. In Ontario, the number of First Nations people speaking Ojibway languages fell 8.7 percent between 2016 and 2021, and people 65 and older are more than twice as likely to speak an Indigenous language as children 14 and under. South of the border the picture is sharper still: estimates put fluent Ojibwe speakers in the United States at roughly a thousand, most of them Elders.</p>
      <p>Put those together and the window is plain. The first-language generation is in its fifties, sixties, and seventies now. The next twenty years decide whether transmission restarts or ends. Nobody, on either side of the border, has an actual count of fluent speakers by name and community. That is the gap this program works inside.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">What the program does</h2>
    <div class="lang-body">
      <p>Four streams, one principle: the technology serves the relationships, not the other way around.</p>
    </div>
    <ol class="lang-streams">
      <li><strong>Record fluent speakers now.</strong> A working pipeline takes a speaker's recordings and produces curated, consent-tracked corpus items: audio, transcription, provenance. The first corpus, drawn from one Elder's public teaching videos and used with his agreement, has 27 curated items. The longer goal is a speaker registry: who the fluent speakers are, where, and what dialect, starting with Sagamok and the North Shore, designed so any community can run its own count.</li>
      <li><strong>Build places to hear the language.</strong> Most revitalization work fails on format, not demand. Classes run for years with barely any regulars. The program's answer is listening-first: nbwaachewin (visiting) evenings where fluent speakers tell stories and learners listen, with no curriculum and no performance pressure, plus standing open online sessions. The generation that grew up hearing the language but does not speak it readily is the first audience.</li>
      <li><strong>Ship a structured course.</strong> A first lesson is built and running: cards with image, audio, Anishinaabemowin, and English, with a practice mode that hides the English. The architecture is one shared core (language data, spaced repetition, audio, consent tracking) serving three audiences: adult community members, youth classrooms, and self-directed remote learners.</li>
      <li><strong>Keep the core open and the content gated.</strong> The code is open source. Another Nation can fork the system and put their own language behind it. The language content itself is community-controlled and never ships with the code. Nothing enters the corpus without a human pass, no AI ever generates Anishinaabemowin for the corpus, and spelling stays exactly as the speaker writes it.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">Why this sits on oiatc.ca</h2>
    <div class="lang-body">
      <p>OIATC's premise is that the communities a system serves should be the ones who choose and govern it. This program is that premise applied to the hardest case: language, where the data is sacred, the speakers are few, and the consent questions are sharpest. Every decision record in the program (Elder-first content, human-curated corpus boundary, orthography preserved as written, machine drafts never treated as truth) is governance before product. Minoo, the community platform OIATC stewards, is the program's long-term home for dictionary, speaker, and dialect data, with consent tracking built into the structure.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">What is settled, what is being decided</h2>
    <div class="lang-body lang-state">
      <p><strong>Settled:</strong> the Elder-first ground rules. The shared-core, three-shells architecture. The first corpus source. The open-code, gated-content license posture.</p>
      <p><strong>Being decided:</strong> the written consent record format that scales past a trusted-collaborator phase. The speaker registry design. The format and cadence of the first community listening sessions. Which community partners carry the youth classroom shell.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">Progress log</h2>
    <div class="lang-log">
      <!-- Newest first. To add an entry, copy one .lang-log__entry block and
           place it at the top of this list. -->
      <div class="lang-log__entry">
        <p class="lang-log__date">2026-06-12</p>
        <p class="lang-log__body">Program plan written, unifying the corpus work, community sessions, course, and platform into one program with a 90-day and 12-month roadmap. This page published.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="lang-log__entry">
        <p class="lang-log__date">2026-05-14 to late May</p>
        <p class="lang-log__body">First corpus built: 27 curated items from roughly 50 public teaching videos. Lesson 1 (kitchen vocabulary, 16 items) shipped as a browser app with a shareable preview for Elder review. Five decision records adopted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="lang-log__entry">
        <p class="lang-log__date">2026-05-14</p>
        <p class="lang-log__body">Project started as parallel R&amp;D alongside Sagamok's accreditation track.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">Take part</h2>
    <div class="lang-body">
      <p>The program is looking for fluent speakers and Elders who want their voice recorded on their own terms, semi-speakers who want somewhere to listen, teachers, researchers who can put rigor behind the speaker count, and developers for the open core. Write to Russell: <a href="mailto:russellsjones@oiatc.ca">russellsjones@oiatc.ca</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lang-sec">
    <h2 class="lang-sec__title">Sources</h2>
    <ul class="lang-sources">
      <li>Statistics Canada and the Office of the Commissioner of Indigenous Languages, "Indigenous Language Families: Algonquian languages," 2021 Census thematic report (March 2025): <a href="https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/41-20-0002/412000022025002-eng.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/41-20-0002/412000022025002-eng.htm</a></li>
      <li>Statistics Canada, "Indigenous languages across Canada," Census in Brief: <a href="https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2021/as-sa/98-200-x/2021012/98-200-x2021012-eng.cfm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2021/as-sa/98-200-x/2021012/98-200-x2021012-eng.cfm</a></li>
      <li>Statistics Canada, The Daily, "Indigenous language families in Canada" (March 31, 2025): <a href="https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/250331/dq250331a-eng.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/250331/dq250331a-eng.htm</a></li>
      <li>University of Minnesota, Ojibwe People's Dictionary, on US fluent-speaker estimates: <a href="https://ojibwe.lib.umn.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://ojibwe.lib.umn.edu/</a></li>
      <li>CBC News on 2021 census data gaps for Indigenous languages: <a href="https://www.cbc.ca/news/indigenous/indigenous-languages-2021-census-data-1.6554041" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.cbc.ca/news/indigenous/indigenous-languages-2021-census-data-1.6554041</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <p class="lang-byline">Russell Jones, on behalf of OIATC. Independent of the bodies named. Corrections welcome.</p>

</article>
{% endblock %}
